a) Introduction

This analysis includes the dataset from the Bonanza Creek LTER, part of the US Long Term Ecological Research Network about Snowshoe Hares, Lepus americanus. Snowshoe hairs are a keystone prey species in the northern boreal forests and their population flucutates over 8-11 year spans (Kielland, 1999). This dataset includes capture-recapture studies of hares at 5 locations in the Tanana valley between the years of 1999 to 2012. This exploratory report explores the relationship between the counts of hares per year, the impact of sex on the hare weight, and the relationship between hind foot length and hare weight.

b) Data and Analyses

In this analysis, the amount of trappings of hares throughout 1999 to 2012 were inconsistent per year, with the maximum amount of trappings in 1999 with a total of 126, and a minimum amount in 2010 with two trappings. The inconsistent counts of hares per year could have an effect on the data analyzed. The sex of the hare significantly had an effect on the hare weight (p = 0.007093), but with only a small effect size (Cohens d = -0.2904674). The hind foot length had a linear relationship with the hare weight with an R^2 value of 0.2988.

c) Exploratory findings

i) Annual juvenile hare trap counts

According to this graph, it looks like the amount of trappings per year decreased by 2001, and then fluctuated throughout the years of 2001-2012. The maximum number of trappings was in 1999 with a total of 126, and the minimum was in 2010 with two trappings. The mean number of trapped hares was 31.5 and the median was 18.5. There was a general trend of an initial decrease but not really any trend past 2001. I would suggest to do a more even number of hare trappings every year in order to standardize the juvenile hare population in future analyses. This would give a more accurate and consistent representation of the hare populations in every year, as a representative sample of 2 in 2010 will not cover the population very well.

The actual difference in means of the male and female hares is 90.468. The mean body weight of the female hares was 855.39g and the males was 945.86g. I ran a two sample t test and cohens d test on female and male hare weights. There was a significant different in body mass, and a small effect size (Cohens d = -0.2904674). The resulting degrees of freedom was 325.02. The p value, the probability that we could have gotten sample means that are least as different as these if the null hypothesis (that they were pulled from populations with the same mean) was true is 0.007093. This means there is a .7% chance we could have gotten these from random chance if they were pulled from populations from the same mean, showing that sex probably has a significant effect on the weight of the hares. The cohen.d test showed us that the d estimate, the effect size, was -0.2904674, a small effect size of the sex of the hare on their weight.

iv) Relationship between juvenile weight and hind foot length

In this exploratory visualization, it looks like a linear relationship does make sense. The points are not exactly linear and the spread grows as the hind foot length increases, but the relationship is still somewhat linear, letting us use a linear model. Now I can model it using lm().

Simple linear regression was used to explore the relationship between hare foot length (mm) and weight (g) across both the male and female hares. A significant regression model was found (\(\beta\) = 0.031, F(1,247) = 105.2, p < 0.001) with an R2 of 0.299.The Multiple R2 value, the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable (weight) that was predictable from the independent variable (hind foot length) was 0.2988. This means that ~30% of the variance in the weight was predictable from the hind foot length. Both the intercept and the weight coefficients were significantly different than 0. The assumptions that we made doing this linear regression were linearity of the relationship between these factors, which was seen in our exploratory graph above, independence of errors, homoscedasticity of the errors, and normality of the error distribution. It would be better to include the hare sex as another variable because we know that the mean weights are different with male and female penguins, even though it was a small effect size. After using the plot() function, graphs 1 and 3 show us that the errors are not very homeodastic,the QQ plot showed us that the residuals were somewhat normal, and graph 4 showed Cooks distance. I would be a little bit concerned homoscedasticity. Here, we see that there is a strong positive correlation between hare hind foot length and weight (r = 0.55, t(247) = 10.26, p < 0.001).

Summary:

  • ~30% of the variance in the weight was predictable from the hind foot length

  • a significant regression model was found
